s a cure for the conformity and alienation they feared was stifling American ingenuity. It was touted as a force of individualism and the human spirit, a new middle-class aspiration that suited the needs of corporate America and the spirit of anticommunism. Amid increasingly rigid systems, creativity took on an air of romance; it was a more democratic quality than genius, but more rarified than mere intelligence. The term eluded clear definition, allowing all sorts of people and institutions to claim it as a solution to their problems, from corporate dullness to urban decline. Today, when creativity is constantly sought after, quantified, and maximized, Franklin’s eye-opening history of the concept helps us to see what it really is, and whom it really serves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.) 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aCreative abilityzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acreativity, psychology, capitalism, Cold War, imagination, cultural history, history of ideas, advertising, creative industries, creative class.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226657998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226657998/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles